    <h1>
      Lakhon Khol
      <br />
      ល្ខោនខោល
    </h1>
    <p class="description">
        Cambodian dance and drama theatre can be performed in three forms. <span>There are two forms in which involves folklore of specific characters such as Hanuman, Preah Ream, etc.</span>
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li class="masked">
          <p>
              <strong>Lakhon Khol</strong> are Cambodian masked dance <br/> dramas that were very traditional plays to tell <br/> Cambodian folklore. Men prefer masked <br/> performances a lot more than Apsara which is <br/> similar to Lakhon Khol but without masks.
            </p>  
          <img src="https://www.blaineharrington.com/img-get2/I0000MXkUy7QERuI/fit=1000x750/20170223-world-12741.jpg" alt="hanuman" width="350px" height="449px">
          <div class="container_one">
            <button class="maskedButton">
            Lakhon Khol
          </button>
          </div> 
        </li>
        <li class="shadowPuppets">
          <p>
            <strong>Lakhon Nang Sbek</strong> is another sacred form of theatre. It is very similar to Chinese Pi Ying Xi. It takes into <br/> the form of 2D shadow puppets. However, the puppeteers are actually shown in the performance where <br/>they dance while controlling the shadow puppets. Two popular genres are Sbek Thom and Sbek Toch.
          </p>
            <img src="https://www.jescaprudencio.com/uploads/2/8/1/3/28133025/17212122-801520469988661-7122233722254137107-o_orig.jpg" alt="Shadow Puppet" width="650px" height="449px">
            <div class="container_two">
             <button class="shadowPuppetButton">
              Sbek Thom
            </button> 
            </div>
        </li>
        <hr/>
